&gt; There really aren&#39;t any studies I can  personally attest to since I have really just begun this learning process  myself.  I will note that it appears to me based solely on observation that  using just the technical bar data is inadequate.  This kind of reminds me  of the problem faced when trying to use neural networks to recognize  speech.  In this instance a simple frame by frame fourier transform of the  data will not produce the patterns necessary for detection.  You  actually have to analyze the spectrogram of varying time periods for those  patterns to develop properly.
&gt;
&gt; It might be more useful to include standard  indicators over differing time periods with other fundamental financial data,  etc.  Perhaps using statistics like those used in digital signal processing  would be a better idea as well.
&gt;
&gt; I think the biggest problem at this point is that  PCs just aren&#39;t quite fast enough or are limited by available RAM.  this is  bound to change very quickly though so developing these systems now makes a lot  of sense to me.
&gt;
&gt; As far as my current implementation is  concerned.  Bascially what I&#39;ve done is developed a backtesting engine  which is utilized by an agent of sorts which randomly selects techical  indicators with varying parameters and runs them against the market data.   This has been marginally effective and I think this has just brought home the  point to me that technical indicators alone are not enough.
&gt;
&gt; My current idea is to replace those algorithmic  technical indicators with small neural networks that I can train to act as  technical indicators.  Not because I necessarily believe this will produce  better results but because I intend to modify my current system to handle neural  networks instead of the predefined indicator classes I&#39;m currently using.   NEAT looks like a good place to start digging into code to do this.
&gt;
&gt; BTW, I&#39;m working in C#.
&gt;
&gt; As far as the time series data, if all you are  looking for are a couple of data sets than you should definately check out  finance.yahoo.com.  You can download CSV files for free.  The oldest I  have going back to the 1960&#39;s (IBM on the NYSE).
&gt;
&gt; If you think you might have a need for ALL of it  then we can make arangements for me to transmit this to you over the  internet.  That file which covers all historical data for all US markets  compressed to just over 500meg using RAR.
